title: CPO futures to trade range-bound
summary: PETALING JAYA: The crude palm oil (CPO) futures contract on Bursa Malaysia Derivatives is expected to trade in range-bound mode this week, as market players lack movement catalysts.
content: Palm oil trader David Ng said the traders lacked fresh leads, mainly on production and export data for this month.

title: Gold futures to remain muted
summary: PETALING JAYA: The gold futures contract on Bursa Malaysia Derivatives is expected to remain muted this week on a lack of interest, a dealer says.
content: Phillip Futures Sdn Bhd dealer Liou Xin Hui said demand for the precious metal on the benchmark United States COMEX market was, however, expected to trade lower.

title: Opec+ seen reviving output in sign of confidence for 2022 demand
summary: NEW YORK: The Organisation of the Petroleum Exporting Countries and its allies (Opec+) are expected to revive more oil supplies when they meet this week, underscoring the group’s optimism in the outlook for global demand.
content: Fifteen of 16 analysts and traders surveyed by Bloomberg predicted the output increase will be approved when the Opec coalition gathers online tomorrow.

In a trading stocks note today, the research housed said the trading volume has increased lately, while the stock is lingering near the multi-month low.

title: Bumi Armada attempting to extend technical rebound, says RHB Retail Research
summary:
KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 3): RHB Retail Research said Bumi Armada Bhd attempted to extend its technical rebound.
In a trading stocks note today, the research housed said that the stock, on several occasions during the past week, tested the 47.5 sen immediate ...
content:
KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 3): RHB Retail Research said Bumi Armada Bhd attempted to extend its technical rebound.

In a trading stocks note today, the research housed said that the stock, on several occasions during the past week, tested the 47.5 sen immediate resistance.

“If the breakout happens, expect the momentum to propel the stock towards the next resistance of 49.5 sen, followed by 53 sen.

“In the event it drops below the 44.5 sen support, the stock may resume the downward movement,” it said.

title: OPEC to meet on Monday to discuss new top official
summary: LONDON: OPEC ministers are due to hold a meeting on Monday to discuss the appointment of a new secretary general, two OPEC sources said, with Kuwait's candidate for the job holding widespread support from the group.
content: Haitham al-Ghais, a former Kuwaiti governor to the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries, is the only candidate for the role, OPEC sources have said.

title: KKMM suggests building higher platforms at 1,000 telecommunication towers hit by floods
summary:
KOTA BHARU (Jan 2): The Ministry of Communications and Multimedia (KKMM) has suggested building higher platforms of around three metres (10 feet) at 1,000 telecommunication towers affected by the recent floods.

content:
KOTA BHARU (Jan 2): The Ministry of Communications and Multimedia (KKMM) has suggested building higher platforms of around three metres (10 feet) at 1,000 telecommunication towers affected by the recent floods.

Communications and Multimedia Minister Tan Sri Annuar Musa said the move is so that damages to the telecommunication towers are reduced and to ensure that communications will not be cut off, especially in the event of disasters.

title: Zafrul: EPF not solution to challenges, retirement savings important
summary: KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 2): The Employees Provident Fund (EPF) should not be seen as a solution or a way to overcome challenges as this will affect the retirement savings of contributors, especially when Malaysia is expected to hit ageing nation status ...
content:
KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 2): The Employees Provident Fund (EPF) should not be seen as a solution or a way to overcome challenges as this will affect the retirement savings of contributors, especially when Malaysia is expected to hit ageing nation status by 2030, said Finance Minister Tengku Datuk Seri Zafrul Abdul Aziz.

"This means that in eight years, retirees or senior citizens will make up 15%, or 5.3 million people, of the population, and eight years is not a long time.

title: KPLB collecting data on flood damages to prepare for repair work, allocations
summary: PUTRAJAYA (Jan 2): The Ministry of Rural Development (KPLB) is collecting data on the damages in flood-hit Hardcore Poor Housing programme, village and rural roads, bridges, drains belonging to surau, childcare centres, kindergartens as well as other amenities under its supervision ...
content:
PUTRAJAYA (Jan 2): The Ministry of Rural Development (KPLB) is collecting data on the damages in flood-hit Hardcore Poor Housing programme, village and rural roads, bridges, drains belonging to surau, childcare centres, kindergartens as well as other amenities under its supervision to prepare for repair works and cost allocation.

Rural Development Minister Datuk Seri Mahdzir Khalid said in this post-flood period KPLB and all its agencies are evaluating damages suffered by flood victims, apart from carrying out clean-up work through its volunteers in Bentong, Hulu Langat, and Banting.

title: Melaka ready to open more PPS if needed — chief minister
summary:
MELAKA (Jan 2): The Melaka government is ready to open more temporary evacuation centres (PPS) if the existing ones are full and there is an increase in the number of flood victims, said Chief Minister Datuk Seri Sulaiman Md Ali.
He ...
content:
MELAKA (Jan 2): The Melaka government is ready to open more temporary evacuation centres (PPS) if the existing ones are full and there is an increase in the number of flood victims, said Chief Minister Datuk Seri Sulaiman Md Ali.

He said the new PPS are needed due to compliance with the standard operating procedures related to physical distancing, issued by the state Health Department.

title: Police, MOH to continue monitoring SOP compliance in Kelantan
summary: KOTA BHARU (Jan 2): The police and the Ministry of Health Ministry (MOH) will continue to deploy teams to monitor and ensure compliance with standard operating procedures (SOPs) as Kelantan moves on to Phase Four of the National Recovery Plan on ...
content:
KOTA BHARU (Jan 2): The police and the Ministry of Health Ministry (MOH) will continue to deploy teams to monitor and ensure compliance with standard operating procedures (SOPs) as Kelantan moves on to Phase Four of the National Recovery Plan on Monday.

Kelantan police chief Datuk Shafien Mamat said this is one of the measures to be taken to curb the spread of Covid-19 in the state.

title: Khairy: Temporary suspension of umrah travel aimed at slowing down Omicron wave
summary: KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 2): The temporary suspension of travel permission to perform the umrah is to slow down the spread of the Covid-19 Omicron variant as data obtained showed that almost 78% of the "presumptive" new Omicron cases are from those returning ...
content:

title: MetMalaysia warns of continuous rain in several states, federal territories
summary:
KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 2): The Malaysian Meteorological Department (MetMalaysia) has issued warning of continuous rain at danger, severe, and alert levels for several states and federal territories until Tuesday (Jan 4).
MetMalaysia in a statement on Sunday announced that the affected states ...
content:
KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 2): The Malaysian Meteorological Department (MetMalaysia) has issued warning of continuous rain at danger, severe, and alert levels for several states and federal territories until Tuesday (Jan 4).

MetMalaysia in a statement on Sunday announced that the affected states and federal territories are Johor, Pahang, Negeri Sembilan, Melaka, Sabah, Kelantan, Terengganu, Perak, Selangor, Kuala Lumpur, and Putrajaya.

Danger-level continuous torrential rain is forecast in Johor involving the districts of Tangkak, Muar, Batu Pahat, Pontian, and Johor Bahru on Sunday.</

title: Number of flood victims continues to increase on Sunday
summary:
KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 2): Continuous heavy rain has resulted in several low-lying areas in seven states to be flooded and more people were being evacuated to relief centres (PPS) on Sunday morning.
In Sabah, Telupid and Sandakan are the two latest ...
content:
KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 2): Continuous heavy rain has resulted in several low-lying areas in seven states to be flooded and more people were being evacuated to relief centres (PPS) on Sunday morning.

In Sabah, Telupid and Sandakan are the two latest districts to be hit by the floods after Kota Marudu, Paitan, and Beluran.

The State Disaster Management Secretariat, in a statement, said with the additional two districts, the number of flood evacuees had increased to 717 people, involving 212 families, from 566 people (182 families) on Saturday night.

title: MySay: Stop the profiteering from human misery in the pandemic
summary:
Migrant workers have made huge changes to their lives and work to adapt to Covid-19. So too have the human traffickers that prey on them.
Migrant workers, especially women migrant workers, have been particularly hard hit by Covid-19.
As with ...
content:
Migrant workers have made huge changes to their lives and work to adapt to Covid-19. So too have the human traffickers that prey on them.

Migrant workers, especially women migrant workers, have been particularly hard hit by Covid-19.

As with previous shocks, migrant workers have found themselves the first to lose jobs. They have borne the brunt of quarantines, curfews, lockdowns and slow vaccine rollouts. Border closures and travel restrictions have prevented them from going home or coming back to work.

content:
KUALA LUMPUR (Jan 2): A total of 22,859,803 individuals or 97.7% of the adult population in the country had completed their Covid-19 vaccination as of Saturday.

Follow our Covid-19 vaccination tracker to see where we are in the race to herd immunity.
